19941007000000000_6	In conventional processing a standard blast furnace requires the two raw ingredients coking coal and iron ore to be processed separately before they are put into the furnace to make molten iron.	convent process standard blast furnac requir two raw ingredi coke coal iron ore process separ befor put furnac make molten iron
19941007000000000_7	Coking coal is turned into burnable coke by baking in ovens.	coke coal turn burnabl coke bake oven
19941007000000000_8	Raw iron ore is converted from its powdered state into lumps in a process called sintering.	raw iron ore convert powder state lump process call sinter
19941007000000000_9	The two materials are then transferred to the blast furnace to be melted into pig iron which is processed into steel.	two materi transfer blast furnac melt pig iron process steel
19941007000000000_10	The Japanese group has removed the need for the separate coking ovens and sinterers by building a blast furnace with two smaller furnaces attached to the top one above the other.	japanes group ha remov need separ coke oven sinter build blast furnac two smaller furnac attach top one abov
19941007000000000_11	The iron ore powder is poured into the top of the structure and passes through the two small furnaces where it is sintered using gases generated when ordinary coal rather than coke is put directly into the main chamber and burned.	iron ore powder pour top structur pass two small furnac sinter use gase gener ordinari coal rather coke put directli main chamber burn
19941007000000000_12	The iron ore passes through the two furnaces at the top and mixes with the coal in the main furnace to produce pig iron.	iron ore pass two furnac top mix coal main furnac produc pig iron
19941007000000000_13	We estimate that the cost of producing steel can be cut by around 10 per cent using this method Kanamori says.	estim cost produc steel cut around per cent use thi method kanamori say
